gomodel:SYNGO_5257  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Similar to ubiquitylation, neddylation requires three sequential reaction steps accomplished by the heterodimeric E1-activating enzyme NAE (Nedd8 activating enzyme), the conjugating enzyme Ubc12 and an as yet incompletely characterized set of E3 ligases (PMID:18793140).\n\nFigure 2: Inhibition of neddylation blocks spine maturation. shRNA knockdown of Ubc12 in DIV12 mouse hippocampal neurons strongly decreased dendritic spine density and increased the number of dendritic filopodia.\n\nFigure 2,3: knockdown of Ubc12 and using NAE inhibitor MLN-4924 (Fig. S2c & PMID:19360080) also reduced dendritic spine maturation.\n\nFigure 4: Neddylation is active in synapses, as demonstrated by live imaging experiments that quantified the rates of de novo growth and elimination of spines in mature cultured neurons (DIV19) treated for 8 h with vehicle or MLN-4924.\n\nFigure 6, 7: molecular characterization of PSD95 (DLG4) neddylation further confirms this process takes place at the postsynapse.. Experimental description: Results, Figure 2 legend: \"DIV12 mouse hippocampal neurons were transfected with the indicated plasmids and treated with vehicle (dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO)) or 1 uM MLN-4924\"\n\nplasmids;\n\" shRNA vectors targeting mouse Nedd8, Ubc12, and Rbx1, as well as a -shRNA control, were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich. Nedd8 (NM_008683) ... Ubc12 (NM_145578)\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" ;
        dc:date           "2023-03-09" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5257" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

